explanation:
Explain why each symbol is required:

- OS_CP_BLOCK_SIZE
  Required to know the size of the local buffer copyblock (sizeof(copyblock) == OS_CP_BLOCK_SIZE * sizeof(uint8)). The MISRA rule concerns accesses beyond buffer bounds, so the precise buffer length is required.

- uint8 (typedef / width)
  Needed to confirm the byte-size of each array element. If uint8 is not 1 byte on the target platform the effective buffer capacity differs; this affects whether reads/writes could overflow copyblock.

- int32 (typedef / width)
  The variables rd_size, wr_size and wr_total are int32. Knowing their width and signedness is necessary to reason about comparisons, conversions (e.g. size_t vs int32), potential truncation or negative values and whether arithmetic/indexing can produce out-of-bounds accesses.

- osal_id_t (typedef)
  Needed to ensure file identifiers are handled correctly by OpenCreate/read/write/close prototypes; not directly about string.h but required to understand side effects and validity checks that might affect control flow (e.g. early exits) relevant to buffer usage.

- OS_read (prototype and contract)
  Critical: must know the function signature (parameter types), that it will not write more than the requested byte count into the provided buffer, and its return semantics (negative on error, zero on EOF, positive <= requested). This guarantees whether rd_size can ever exceed sizeof(copyblock) and thus whether copyblock writes could overflow.

- OS_write (prototype and contract)
  Required to confirm how partial writes are reported (wr_size), whether it accepts the byte count exactly as passed, and whether it can write beyond the supplied buffer. The loop assumes partial writes are possible (wr_size >=0 and < remaining) and uses &copyblock[wr_total] safely only if rd_size was bounded by the buffer size.

- OS_OpenCreate (prototype and error/return semantics)
  Needed to confirm that file1/file2 are valid when OS_read/OS_write are called and to understand error return codes and when the copy loop is entered. Also ensures no implicit buffer or pointer aliasing semantics from OpenCreate affect read/write behavior.

- OS_CHECK_POINTER (definition / behavior)
  This macro/function validates src and dest. Knowing whether it returns, aborts, or modifies control flow is necessary to determine whether the rest of the function can assume non-NULL pointers; though not directly a string.h function, it affects whether subsequent operations run.

- OS_SUCCESS (value)
  The copy loop and error handling depend on the numeric value tested against return_code. Knowing the exact value/semantics is necessary to reason about which branches execute and whether read/write calls occur.

- OS_OBJECT_ID_UNDEFINED (value)
  Used to initialize file1/file2. Knowing its value/semantics clarifies whether OS_close is called and whether file handles are valid when read/write occur; affects control-flow reasoning relevant to buffer usage.

Notes:
- The target function does not directly call any standard <string.h> functions. However, to certify it does not indirectly cause out-of-bounds accesses via library wrappers, the OS_read/OS_write contracts and the buffer size/type information are essential.
- If available, include any documentation or implementation details for OS_read/OS_write that state they internally use memcpy/memmove/etc. If internal string.h usage exists, those implementations and their parameter handling must be checked as well.
